arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. Probable early collapse of the Baroque Room and damage occurs in both the Anteroom and Shrine Room. The tabun in Room A is used to store CE 1st c. Nabataean fine wares. East 'Cistern" used as a dump. Bath Complex built.

This was a dump locus, which appeared white because of the large amount of plaster, both decayed and preserved, which was mixed with the soil. This was a very thick locus that had multiple strata within it and covered the entire trench. Although it was all excavated as one locus, the balk revealed that there were different concentrations of plaster at different elevations within the locus. Many spectacular finds came from this locus, which was partially mixed with Locus 2 above it.
Use of the cistern as a Nabataean dump for plaster, pottery, and all sorts of other material. Ceramics date this deposit to the early CE second century. (Phasing may include late Phase V).
